  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between oaked and unoaked Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Oaked Chardonnays undergo fermentation or aging in oak barrels, developing rich flavors of vanilla, butter, and toast, with a creamy texture from malolactic fermentation. Unoaked versions are fermented in stainless steel, preserving bright acidity and pure fruit flavors like green apple, citrus, and mineral notes. The best choice depends on your preference for rich, complex wines versus crisp, refreshing styles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I identify a high-quality Chardonnay without tasting it first?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for specific vineyard designations rather than generic regional labels, as single-vineyard Chardonnays typically offer better quality and terroir expression. Check for vintage dates within 2-5 years for unoaked styles and 3-8 years for premium oaked versions. Producer reputation matters significantly—established names like Kistler, Aubert, or Domaine Leflaive consistently deliver exceptional quality, though newer boutique producers often offer excellent value.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve premium Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve oaked Chardonnays at 50-55°F to allow their complex flavors and creamy texture to fully develop, while unoaked versions are best at 45-50°F to preserve their crisp acidity and fresh fruit character. Remove the wine from the refrigerator 10-15 minutes before serving oaked styles, or 5-10 minutes for unoaked versions. Proper temperature is crucial because overly cold wine mutes the nuanced flavors that make premium Chardonnay special.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Chardonnay a good wine for beginners to explore?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Chardonnay is excellent for beginners because it offers such diverse style options, from crisp and refreshing to rich and buttery, allowing newcomers to discover their preferences. The grape's food-friendly nature makes it versatile for pairing experiments, while its widespread availability means you can easily find quality examples at various price points. Start with moderately oaked versions from Sonoma Coast or Chablis to experience balanced complexity without overwhelming richness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best value alternatives to expensive Burgundian Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sonoma Coast and Russian River Valley Chardonnays offer similar elegance and mineral complexity at 30-50% less cost than premier Burgundy. Cool-climate Australian regions like Adelaide Hills and Tasmania produce exceptional Chardonnays with Burgundian finesse at even better price points. For the ultimate value, explore Chablis Premier Cru from producers like William Fèvre or Louis Michel, which deliver authentic mineral-driven Burgundian character without the premium Côte d'Or pricing.</p>
